            reviewDate: 'August 4, 2022',
            semester: 'summer 2022',
            review: "I took this in the summer, which contributed to the difficulty of the course and got an A. With that said though, I kept coming back to the question: \"Why do we take classes?\"\nI think for most people, the number one reason is to learn. Which is why I found this course such a paradox. I learned a ton. My Python skills and understanding of OOP increased, I have a stronger understanding of the random forest algorithm and recursion. I gained experience in reinforcement learning. I learned a lot about the stock market and technical analysis. But I just found the course overall to be a tremendous drag. This is my 9th course in the OMSA program and the only one where I had to force myself to put in the needed time. The class just drained my motivation.\nOthers have spoken about the unneeded complexity of the assignments, and I agree. They were ridiculous at times. The grading is harsh and you can lose a large amount of points for trivial things. Also, the correct answers are never shared.\nThere are two multiple choice tests in addition to the eight assignments. They never reveal to you what you missed on the exams. You are just given a score about a week after taking it.\nThe projects take weeks to get graded and they all build on each other. So if you don't understand something, you're in trouble.\nOne last thing I found annoying is that the lectures were created 5+ years ago. Many of the most important lectures are webcam videos of the previous professor writing on a whiteboard. When those were filmed it was done in conjunction with the live class with the professor answering questions live on Piazza. These need to be redone.\nOne last last thing is the current professor. I admire Dr. Joyner. I have read his Reddit posts and his thoughts on online learning. He clearly cares deeply about this and has done a lot for the OMS programs. However, he does not make a single appearance in this class. Not one. This is a class entirely lead by the TA's (who were pretty good). But I was hoping to have Dr. Joyner make at least one live session or even just a post on Ed.\nSo this class has overall positive reviews, but for me it is not something I would ever want to do again. As I said at the beginning, I learned a lot. But it was a tedious and annoying process instead of the rewarding one I have had in previous classes.",
